6 PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY

Wynnewood is continuously investigating and reviewing technology and/or applications that could possibly enhance its safety efforts. These currently include:
- Fire water systems;
- deluge fire protection additions;
- Emergency Isolation Valves;
- Dual pump seals;
- Alternative technologies to replace HF; and
- Personnel accountability systems.

arily uses the hazard and operability analysis (HAZOP) and What-if/Checklist techniques to perform these evaluations. The analyses are conducted using a team of refinery personnel who have operating and maintenance experience as well as engineering expertise, and may include third parties. This team identifies and evaluates hazards of the process as well as accident prevention and mitigation measures. The team makes suggestions for additional prevention and/or mitigation measures when the team believes such measures are needed. Any identified risks are promptly addressed. Resolution of each finding is documented and records of the analyses are retained.

To ensure that the process controls and/or process hazards do not significantly deviate from the original design safety features, the refinery periodically updates and revalidates the hazard analysis results. These periodic reviews are conducted at least every five years unless review is warranted sooner due to a significant change at the refinery. Once again, the reviews are documented and records of the review are retained.

Operating Procedures
The refinery maintains written procedures at the refinery that address various modes of process operations such as: 
(1) initial start-up; 
(2) normal operations; 
(3) temporary operations; 
(4) emergency shutdown; 
(5) emergency operations; 
(6) normal shutdown; and 
(7) startup following a turnaround, or after an emergency shutdown. 
Operating procedures are reviewed periodically and as operational changes are introduced and annually certified as current and accurate. Both operators and technical staff participate in the review and certification process.

Operating procedures provide current, clearly written instructions for operating the processes. Instructions include applicable safety precautions and appropriate information on safety implications. Operating procedures ensure that all employees operate the processes in a prescribed, consistent, and safe manner.

